Comment:
richkitch v saguaro.  This was a Team Match. 
Saguaro opens. Saguaro does not open e4 or d4.
Black responds forcefully.
White mirrors.
Now, Black is developing the Queen Bishop common in the Caro-Kann defense....a good move.
White develops along a lot of paths to deal with this.
Black does another Caro-Kann move to make infantry and Q bishop on defense and ready attack.
All Black has to do for this is attack the bishop in a common Caro-Kann fashion...
...and so he does!
Bishop backs off.
Usually in Caro we want the knights to work as a pair as in a pair of rooks.  Black manages to achieve this with a more forward move ready to have the King Knight to become a duo pair....
White is opening for the King Bishop and reinforcing while doing so.
Black is on the attack now forcing the Queen Bishop to g3....
...and there it is.
Now I am realizing Black is being rather offensive considering Black is usually defensive. Perhaps Black wants to advance more infantry (c6) while netting White into a restrictive environment.
Black realizes taking the King Bishop is as the cost of developing White's Queen!
Black decides to do another Caro-Kann move moving a night into a "corner" where it serves while Black develops at the cost of White.
Immediately I see c6 for Black...
And so it is!
The King Bishop on White is now backing up!
I'd swear Black knows the Caro-Kann.  Black is doing from a modified Caro-Kann when White opens Knight to f3--really a weak open by White. In my world White Opens e4 or d4 or loses.
